{
  "doc_id": "42428",
  "text": "In order to improve the performance of MEMS gyroscopes, several methods including temperature control, electrostatic tuning, and optimal design were presented [CITATION_1] [4] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . With these methods, the polysilicon DRG that was implemented through the epitaxial silicon encapsulation process and had a Q value of 50 k at a resonant frequency of 264 kHz was reported in [CITATION_6] . Later, the <100> silicon gyroscope of similar geometry and process is presented in [CITATION_7] , the Q value of it was larger than 100 k on n = 3 modes at a resonant frequency of 70 kHz, and the mean frequency split of it was 21 Hz. A ring gyroscope operated at the trefoil mode (n = 3) with a Q value of 10 k in vacuum and a mean frequency split ratio of 225 ppm at 130 kHz is achieved in [CITATION_8] . The DRG with a Q value of~1.3 M and 40 ppm frequency split at 2.745 MHz is presented in [CITATION_9] . On the whole, it can be seen that all of the methods focus on increasing the frequency split and decreasing the Q value.",
